f98bd5d2-010e-45fd-8a13-f8a939043604	ff68e952-b7ee-4034-af62-07c9d79660f1	The Psychology of Becoming Anew	\N	<p>Before embarking on any journey of change, it is crucial to understand the psychological terrain. Personal reinvention is not a modern whim but a natural, recurring part of the human experience, governed by predictable internal and external forces.</p>	https://media.lilde.com/media/%40_The-Stable-Reset/MP3/002.mp3	\N	\N	2	STANDARD	0	0	2025-10-17 16:40:10.024858	2025-11-17 14:33:28.356552	light	0.00	0.00	t	\N	\N	\N	\N	2025-11-18 01:00:00
f14b15a0-62f1-471e-addf-54bc132accd5	ff68e952-b7ee-4034-af62-07c9d79660f1	The Life Audit & 'Wheel of Life' Assessment	\N	<p>A life audit is a structured method for gaining a clear, objective snapshot of one's current reality across various domains. The 'Wheel of Life' is a popular coaching tool that provides a powerful visual representation of this audit, helping to move beyond a vague sense of dissatisfaction to pinpoint specific areas that require attention. The exercise involves several steps. First, define categories by identifying 8 to 10 central domains of life. While these can be customized, common categories include: Career/Work, Finances, Health (Physical &amp; Mental), Relationships (Partner/Family), Social Life (Friends), Personal Growth, Physical Environment, and Fun/Recreation. Second, rate satisfaction on a scale of 1 (very dissatisfied) to 10 (fully satisfied), rate the current level of fulfillment in each category. This requires honest reflection, trusting one's initial instinct rather than overthinking the score. Third, plot the wheel by drawing a circle and dividing it into spokes, one for each category. Mark the satisfaction score on each spoke (with 1 being at the center and 10 at the outer edge) and connect the dots. Fourth, analyze the shape. The resulting shape provides an immediate visual representation of life balance. A "bumpy" or lopsided wheel clearly indicates which areas are thriving and which are neglected, creating a powerful impetus for change. A low score in a particular area often reveals the root of general dissatisfaction. To facilitate a deeper audit, you can use probing questions to guide the rating process. For Career / Work, ask: Does my work feel fulfilling and aligned with my skills? Am I growing professionally? Do I feel valued and respected in my role? For Finances &amp; Money, ask: Do I feel in control of my financial situation? Am I earning enough to meet my needs and goals? Am I saving and investing for the future? For Health &amp; Wellness, ask: How energetic do I feel on a daily basis? Am I satisfied with my diet, exercise, and sleep habits? Am I effectively managing stress? For Relationships (Friends &amp; Family), ask: Are my relationships with family and friends supportive and energizing? Do I feel connected to the people who matter most to me? For Love &amp; Romance, ask: Am I satisfied with my romantic life? Do I feel seen, cherished, and secure with my partner? If single, do I feel content with my status? For Personal Growth, ask: Am I actively learning new things or developing new skills? Do I feel I am evolving into a better version of myself? Am I challenging myself? For Fun &amp; Recreation, ask: Am I making enough time for hobbies and activities I genuinely enjoy? Do I feel a sense of playfulness and adventure in my life? For Physical Environment, ask: Does my home and work environment feel peaceful, organized, and supportive? Does my physical space drain or energize me?</p>	https://media.lilde.com/media/%40_The-Stable-Reset/MP3/007.mp3	\N	\N	7	OVERFLOW	0	0	2025-10-17 16:40:10.024858	2025-11-07 16:44:37.241543	light	0.00	0.00	t	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
