f9a77f48-f2a4-44a2-82db-4bbfb0a0706b	ff68e952-b7ee-4034-af62-07c9d79660f1	The Three Types of Job Crafting	\N	<p>First, Task Crafting. This involves altering the number, scope, or nature of daily tasks. It is about actively shaping the boundaries of one's job. An individual might take on more of the tasks they find energizing and fewer of those they find draining. This could mean delegating a repetitive administrative task to focus more on a creative project, or volunteering to mentor a new team member to satisfy a passion for teaching. Second, Relational Crafting. This focuses on changing the nature or extent of interactions with others at work. An employee might choose to spend more time with colleagues who are energizing and supportive, or intentionally build relationships with clients to better understand the real-world impact of their work. This could be as simple as scheduling a monthly lunch with someone from a different department or as involved as creating a new collaborative task force. Third, Cognitive Crafting. This is the most internal form of crafting, involving a deliberate change in how one perceives their job to imbue it with greater meaning and purpose. It is about reframing the "why" behind the work. For example, a hospital cleaner can view their job not as simply mopping floors, but as contributing to a safe and healing environment for patients. An accountant can see their work not as crunching numbers, but as providing the financial clarity that allows a business to thrive and employ people. This shift in perspective can transform a mundane task into a meaningful contribution.</p>	https://media.lilde.com/media/%40_The-Stable-Reset/MP3/030.mp3	\N	\N	30	OVERFLOW	0	0	2025-10-17 16:40:10.024858	2025-11-07 16:46:31.511463	light	0.00	0.00	t	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
512479d4-6bb9-4e19-9dd2-f76eaea2c8e2	ff68e952-b7ee-4034-af62-07c9d79660f1	A Practical Job Crafting Exercise	\N	<p>A structured approach can make job crafting more intentional and effective. First, create a "Before Sketch". Over the course of a week, create a detailed list of all tasks, responsibilities, and interactions that make up the job. For each item, note whether it is energizing, draining, or neutral. This provides a clear diagnostic of the current state. Second, connect to values and strengths. Review the core values and strengths identified in Part I. Analyze the "Before Sketch" to see how well the current role aligns with these personal drivers. Where are the connections? Where are the disconnects? Third, design an "After Diagram". Brainstorm specific, small changes using the three crafting techniques. The goal is to create a redesigned role that maximizes energizing tasks and interactions aligned with one's values, while minimizing or reframing the draining ones. This diagram becomes a personal action plan. Examples of Task Crafting include taking on a new project that utilizes a personal strength, delegating or swapping a task you find draining, finding ways to introduce a passion into daily work, experimenting with new tools or methods, or proposing a new initiative. Examples of Relational Crafting include scheduling regular check-ins with a supportive colleague, offering to mentor a new employee, spending less time with negative colleagues, building stronger connections with clients, or organizing a team social event. Examples of Cognitive Crafting include reframing the importance of a less enjoyable task, creating a "done list" at the end of each day, reminding yourself of the broader mission of the organization, focusing on how your job provides for your life outside of work, or viewing challenges as opportunities to learn.</p>	https://media.lilde.com/media/%40_The-Stable-Reset/MP3/031.mp3	\N	\N	31	OVERFLOW	0	0	2025-10-17 16:40:10.024858	2025-11-07 1