3df7c146-3229-4160-9634-edbe0be58c21	96e40a41-0c6b-4de6-bae7-993aae2c7925	The Turtle's Unshakeable Foundation	\N	The Turtle carries its home on its backthere is no separation between the Turtle and its shell, between being and dwelling. This is the teaching of Truth: that truth is not something external to be discovered or acquired but the foundation you already stand on. The Turtle moves slowly, deliberately, because it knows that rushing toward truth is a contradictiontruth reveals itself in its own time to those patient enough to perceive it. In our world of instant information and competing narratives, where "truth" has become a political football, the Turtle reminds us that there is a deeper truth beneath the noise: the truth of natural law, of cause and effect, of reciprocity and balance. You cannot violate these laws without consequences, no matter how cleverly you rationalize or what ideology you invoke. The Turtle teaches that the good life is built on this foundation of natural law, and that attempting to build on any other ground will eventually collapse.	https://media.lilde.com/media/@_The-Architecture-of-Belonging/012.mp3	\N	\N	12	STANDARD	0	0	2025-11-24 18:25:32.150616	2025-11-24 18:25:32.150616	light	0.00	0.00	t	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
c7bad623-b652-4326-bb86-aff1c6fcf2f9	96e40a41-0c6b-4de6-bae7-993aae2c7925	The Courage of Generosity	\N	Indigenous economies operated on a principle that seems absurd to modern thinking: the wealthiest person was not the one who accumulated the most but the one who gave away the most. In the Lakota giveaway ceremony and the Pacific Northwest potlatch, individuals and families would distribute their possessions to the community, sometimes keeping very little for themselves. This was not nave altruism but sophisticated economics. In a society based on reciprocity, generosity creates social capital, weaves networks of mutual obligation, and ensures that resources flow to where they're needed most. The courage required for generosity is the courage to trust the web, to believe that when you give, you will be given to in your time of need. This trust has been eroded by centuries of colonialism, capitalism, and individualism, leaving us clutching our possessions in fear. Yet the practice of generosity remains a pathway back to belonging, a way to prove to ourselves that we are held by something larger than our own anxious efforts.	https://media.lilde.com/media/@_The-Architecture-of-Belonging/013.mp3	\N	\N	13	STANDARD	0	0	2025-11-24 18:25:32.150616	2025-11-24 18:25:32.150616	light	0.00	0.00	t	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
4cbc9a6e-c892-42c1-bdf2-bd9dbe3f998a	69121c77-2707-4393-8736-02f1859f54c7	Teaching Five: Preparing the Final Song	\N	<p>"Prepare a noble death song for the day when you go over the great divide." In our tradition, a warrior prepares their death songnot out of morbidity, but out of clarity. This song says: "This is who I am. This is what I stood for. This is how I lived." Your death song is not written in a day. It is composed through a lifetime of choices. Each act of courage adds a note. Each truth spoken adds a verse. Each love given adds harmony. To prepare your death song is to live with the end always visible, not to make you fearful, but to make you focused. When you know you must one day stand before the Creator and sing of your life, you become very careful about what notes you add to that song. Your lesson: If you had to sing your death song todayright nowwhat would it say? Would it be a song of courage or of hiding? Of love or of coldness? Of truth or of deception? Begin now to compose a song worthy of singing when you cross over. Live the verses you wish to sing. This teaching requires courage to face. Sit with it until you find that courage. Then proceed.</p>	https://media.lilde.com/media/@_sacred_teachings_guided_journey/006.mp3	https://media.lilde.com/media/_images/lilde_080.jpeg	\N	6	OVERFLOW	0	0	2025-11-20 17:42:23.695504	2025-11-20 18:45:48.811429	\N	0.00	0.00	t	\N	\N	\N	\N	2025-11-21 01:00:00
b6d1f9df-0ef8-4714-b8e9-3a733878791f	69121c77-2707-4393-8736-02f1859f54c7	Teaching Ten: The Two Ways of Dying	\N	<p>"When it comes your time to die, be not like those whose hearts are filled with the fear of death, so that when their time comes they weep and pray for a little more time to live their lives over again in a different way." There are two ways to approach the end. The first way is filled with regret. These are the ones who, at the final moment, realize they lived a life that was not theirs. They followed others' paths. They hid their truth. They let fear choose their actions. They postponed their real living, always saying "tomorrow, tomorrow." And now there are no tomorrows left, and they weep for all the life they never lived. This weeping is not the sadness of leavingit is the agony of never arriving. It is the grief of looking back and seeing a trail of unlived moments, unspoken words, unloved loves, untaken courage. They beg for more time, not because life was so sweet, but because they finally see what life could have been and they missed it. Do you see why this matters now, while you still have mornings ahead of you? The time to live the life you will be proud of is now. Not when you are old. Not when you are comfortable. Not when you are ready. Now. Your lesson: If you died today and could look back at your life, what would you regret? What would you wish you had done differently? These answers are not meant to torment youthey are meant to guide you. You still have time. Use it. Sit with this uncomfortable truth. Let it burn away what is false. Then move to the final teaching.</p>	https://media.lilde.com/media/@_sacred_teachings_guided_journey/011.mp3	https://media.lilde.com/media/_images/lilde_080.jpeg	\N	11	OVERFLOW	0	0	2025-11-20 17:42:23.695504	2025-11-20 17:52:38.03616	\N	0.00	0.00	t	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
ee8c44bc-577b-4dd7-8e69-81c8a74a1e1c	96e40a41-0c6b-4de6-bae7-993aae2c7925	Prayer as Ecological Feedback	\N	When Indigenous peoples pray before harvesting a plant or hunting an animal, modern observers often see this as quaint superstition. But these prayers are actually sophisticated ecological feedback loops. The prayer requires the harvester to pause, to truly see the being they're about to take, to feel gratitude, to assess whether the harvest is necessary and sustainable. This moment of consciousness prevents thoughtless extraction and overconsumption. If you must express thanks and explain your need to every plant you pick, you won't clear-cut the forest. If you must apologize to every fish you catch, you won't overfish the stream. The prayers create a governor on human appetite, a built-in restraint that market economics and bureaucratic regulation have never been able to replicate. The good life includes these moments of acknowledgment, these pauses that interrupt the automaticity of taking and remind us that every gift comes with responsibility.	https://media.lilde.com/media/@_The-Architecture-of-Belonging/014.mp3	\N	\N	14	STANDARD	0	0	2025-11-24 18:25:32.150616	2025-11-24 18:25:32.150616	light	0.00	0.00	t	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
002a27d3-31c3-4f31-a95c-efed832edf53	96e40a41-0c6b-4de6-bae7-993aae2c7925	The Seven Generations Compass	\N	When the Haudenosaunee people make decisions, they consider the impact on seven generations into the future. This is not a metaphor but a literal practice: envisioning your great-great-great-great-grandchildren and asking whether your choice today will honor or harm their inheritance. This intergenerational perspective is nearly absent from modern decision-making, where quarterly earnings reports and election cycles create a tyranny of the immediate. We harvest old-growth forests for short-term profit, we release carbon we know will warm the planet for centuries, we create nuclear waste that remains toxic for millenniaall because we've lost the seven-generation compass. Adopting this practice requires imagination and discipline: regularly visualizing the children of the future, making them as real in your mind as your own siblings or neighbors, and letting their needs influence your choices. This is not selflessness but enlightened self-interest, because your DNA, your stories, your legacy live on in those future generations.	https://media.lilde.com/media/@_The-Architecture-of-Belonging/015.mp3	\N	\N	15	STANDARD	0	0	2025-11-24 18:25:32.150616	2025-11-24 18:25:32.150616	light	0.00	0.00	t	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
